          "text": "Okay, let's try to solve this problem step by step. First, let's make sure I understand what's being asked. We have an envelope function \u0398(\u03c1) = exp(-(\u03c1/\u03c1_c)^\u03b1), and we need to find the minimum pair (\u03b1, \u03c1_c) such that two boundary conditions are satisfied: \n\n1. At the solar system density \u03c1_\u2609 = 10 g/cm\u00b3, \u0398(\u03c1_\u2609) = 10\u207b\u00b3 (Cassini ceiling).\n2. At the cosmological density \u03c1_cosm = 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 g/cm\u00b3, \u0398(\u03c1_cosm) = 0.99 (cosmological visibility floor).\n\nFirst, let's write down the two equations from the boundary conditions.\n\nFor the first condition (R1):\n\u0398(\u03c1_\u2609) = exp(-(\u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1) = 10\u207b\u00b3.\n\nTaking the natural logarithm of both sides:\n-(\u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1 = ln(10\u207b\u00b3) = -3 ln(10) \u2248 -6.907755.\n\nSo, (\u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1 = 3 ln(10) \u2248 6.907755. Let's call this Equation (1).\n\nFor the second condition (R2):\n\u0398(\u03c1_cosm) = exp(-(\u03c1_cosm / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1) = 0.99.\n\nTaking the natural logarithm of both sides:\n-(\u03c1_cosm / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1 = ln(0.99) \u2248 -0.01005034.\n\nSo, (\u03c1_cosm / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1 = 0.01005034. Let's call this Equation (2).\n\nNow, to isolate \u03b1, we can take the ratio of Equation (1) to Equation (2). Let's denote:\n\nLet\u2019s define x = \u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_c and y = \u03c1_cosm / \u03c1_c. Then Equation (1) is x^\u03b1 = 6.907755, and Equation (2) is y^\u03b1 = 0.01005034.\n\nTaking the ratio of Equation (1) to Equation (2): (x/y)^\u03b1 = 6.907755 / 0.01005034 \u2248 687.3.\n\nBut x/y = (\u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_c) / (\u03c1_cosm / \u03c1_c) = \u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_cosm = 10 / 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 = 10\u00b3\u2070.\n\nSo, (10\u00b3\u2070)^\u03b1 = 687.3.\n\nTaking the natural logarithm of both sides: \u03b1 * 30 * ln(10) = ln(687.3).\n\nCalculating ln(687.3) \u2248 6.5327.\n\nln(10) \u2248 2.302585, so 30 * ln(10) \u2248 69.07755.\n\nThus, \u03b1 \u2248 6.5327 / 69.07755 \u2248 0.09457.\n\nWait, let me check that calculation again. Let's compute it more precisely.\n\nFirst, 6.907755 / 0.01005034 = 6.907755 / 0.01005034 \u2248 687.3 (exact value: 6.90775527898214 / 0.0100503358513792 \u2248 687.300).\n\nThen, (\u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_cosm) = 10 / 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 = 10\u00b3\u2070, so (10\u00b3\u2070)^\u03b1 = 687.3.\n\nTaking log base 10: \u03b1 * 30 = log10(687.3) \u2248 2.8372.\n\nThus, \u03b1 \u2248 2.8372 / 30 \u2248 0.09457.\n\nAlternatively, using natural logs: ln(687.3) \u2248 6.5327, ln(10\u00b3\u2070) = 30 ln(10) \u2248 69.07755, so \u03b1 \u2248 6.5327 / 69.07755 \u2248 0.09457. That seems right.\n\nNow, let's verify with the exact values.\n\nFrom Equation (1): (\u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1 = 3 ln(10) \u2248 6.90775527898.\n\nFrom Equation (2): (\u03c1_cosm / \u03c1_c)^\u03b1 = -ln(0.99) \u2248 0.01005033585.\n\nLet\u2019s denote k = \u03c1_c. Then:\n\n(10 / k)^\u03b1 = 6.90775527898,\n\n(10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 / k)^\u03b1 = 0.01005033585.\n\nLet\u2019s take the ratio of the first to the second: (10 / 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079)^\u03b1 = 6.90775527898 / 0.01005033585 \u2248 687.3.\n\nSo, (10\u00b3\u2070)^\u03b1 = 687.3, so \u03b1 = log(687.3) / log(10\u00b3\u2070) = log(687.3) / 30.\n\nUsing log base 10: log10(687.3) \u2248 2.8372, so \u03b1 \u2248 2.8372 / 30 \u2248 0.09457.\n\nNow, let's solve for k (\u03c1_c) using one of the equations. Let's use Equation (2):\n\n(10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 / k)^\u03b1 = 0.01005033585.\n\nSo, 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 / k = (0.01005033585)^(1/\u03b1).\n\nThus, k = 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 / (0.01005033585)^(1/\u03b1).\n\nWe have \u03b1 \u2248 0.09457, so 1/\u03b1 \u2248 10.574.\n\nCompute (0.01005033585)^10.574.\n\nFirst, 0.01005033585 = 1.005033585 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b2.\n\nSo, (1.005033585 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b2)^10.574 = (1.005033585)^10.574 \u00d7 10^(-2\u00d710.574) = (1.005033585)^10.574 \u00d7 10^(-21.148).\n\n(1.005033585)^10.574 \u2248 e^(10.574 \u00d7 0.0050125) \u2248 e^(0.0530) \u2248 1.0545 (since ln(1.005) \u2248 0.0049875, so 10.574 \u00d7 0.0049875 \u2248 0.0528, so e^0.0528 \u2248 1.0543).\n\nThus, approximately 1.0543 \u00d7 10^(-21.148) \u2248 1.0543 \u00d7 10^(-21.148).\n\n10^(-21.148) = 10^(-21) \u00d7 10^(-0.148) \u2248 10^(-21) \u00d7 0.711 \u2248 7.11 \u00d7 10^(-22).\n\nSo, k \u2248 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 / (7.11 \u00d7 10^(-22)) \u2248 1.406 \u00d7 10^(-8) g/cm\u00b3.\n\nWait, let's compute it more accurately.\n\nFirst, let's compute (0.01005033585)^(1/\u03b1) where \u03b1 \u2248 0.09457.\n\nLet\u2019s use natural logs:\n\nln(0.01005033585) = -4.59988 (since ln(0.01) = -4.60517, so 0.01005 is slightly larger, so ln(0.01005) \u2248 -4.59988).\n\nThus, (1/\u03b1) * ln(0.01005033585) = (1/0.09457) * (-4.59988) \u2248 10.574 * (-4.59988) \u2248 -48.65.\n\nThus, (0.01005033585)^(1/\u03b1) = e^(-48.65) \u2248 1.3 \u00d7 10^(-21) (since e^(-46) \u2248 1.3 \u00d7 10^(-20), so e^(-48.65) = e^(-46) * e^(-2.65) \u2248 1.3 \u00d7 10^(-20) * 0.0707 \u2248 9.2 \u00d7 10^(-22)).\n\nWait, let's compute e^(-48.65):\n\n48.65 / ln(10) \u2248 48.65 / 2.3026 \u2248 21.13, so e^(-48.65) = 10^(-21.13) \u2248 7.4 \u00d7 10^(-22).\n\nSo, k = 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 / (7.4 \u00d7 10^(-22)) \u2248 1.35 \u00d7 10^(-8) g/cm\u00b3.\n\nLet's check with Equation (1) to verify.\n\nFrom Equation (1): (10 / k)^\u03b1 = 6.907755.\n\nk = 1.35 \u00d7 10^(-8), so 10 / k = 10 / 1.35 \u00d7 10^8 \u2248 7.407 \u00d7 10^8.\n\n(7.407 \u00d7 10^8)^0.09457.\n\nTake natural log: 0.09457 * ln(7.407 \u00d7 10^8) = 0.09457 * (ln(7.407) + 8 ln(10)) \u2248 0.09457 * (2.002 + 18.4207) \u2248 0.09457 * 20.4227 \u2248 1.932.\n\ne^1.932 \u2248 6.9, which matches 6.907755. Good.\n\nNow, let's do this more precisely. Let's use the exact values.\n\nLet\u2019s denote:\n\nLet A = 3 ln(10) = 6.90775527898214,\n\nB = -ln(0.99) = 0.0100503358513792,\n\nr = \u03c1_\u2609 / \u03c1_cosm = 10 / 10\u207b\u00b2\u2079 = 10\u00b3\u2070.\n\nFrom the t